{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17641507","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17641507"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T19:27:32+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T19:27:32+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17883"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17883","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17883"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10597"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78734"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10597","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10597"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17883"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64078"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"10068"},{"type":"tags","id":"10266"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24698"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24700"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78734","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/78734"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003ESkeletal muscle tissue is metabolically active and can both store and utilise glucose. However, unlike the liver, muscle tissue cannot release glucose into the bloodstream.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following enzymes is absent in skeletal muscle tissue, preventing glucose release into the bloodstream?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Fructose-1,6-bisphosphatase","Glucose-1-phosphatase","Glucose-6-phosphatase","Phosphoenolpyruvate carboxykinase","Pyruvate carboxylase"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ESkeletal muscle tissue lacks \u003Cstrong\u003Eglucose-6-phosphatase\u003C/strong\u003E, which is the enzyme necessary for converting glucose-6-phosphate into free glucose. This enzyme is present in the liver and kidneys, allowing these organs to release glucose into the bloodstream. The absence of glucose-6-phosphatase in muscle means that glucose-6-phosphate must either be used for glycolysis or stored as glycogen.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFructose-1,6-bisphosphatase\u003C/strong\u003E - This enzyme is present in muscle and is involved in gluconeogenesis but is not responsible for the final step of glucose release\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGlucose-1-phosphatase\u003C/strong\u003E - This enzyme does not exist in mammalian metabolism\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPhosphoenolpyruvate carboxykinase\u003C/strong\u003E - This enzyme is involved in gluconeogenesis but not in the final step of glucose release\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPyruvate carboxylase\u003C/strong\u003E - This enzyme catalyses the first committed step of gluconeogenesis but is not involved in glucose release\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis metabolic arrangement ensures that muscle tissue can take up and store glucose but cannot release it back into circulation, maintaining glucose homeostasis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Muscles cannot produce free glucose because they lack glucose-6-phosphatase.","Glucose-6-phosphatase is an enzyme that converts glucose-6-phosphate to free glucose, a step that occurs in the liver and kidneys but not in muscle tissue.","The absence of glucose-6-phosphatase means muscle cells must either use glucose-6-phosphate for glycolysis or store it as glycogen."],"references":["Bender, D. A., \u0026 Cunningham, S. M. (2021). Introduction to nutrition and metabolism. CRC Press","Salway, J. G. (2016). Metabolism at a Glance. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Chandel NS. Amino Acid Metabolism. Cold Spring Harb Perspect Biol. 2021 Apr 1;13(4):a040584. doi: 10.1101/cshperspect.a040584. PMID: 33795250; PMCID: PMC8015690","Ling ZN, Jiang YF, Ru JN, Lu JH, Ding B, Wu J. Amino acid metabolism in health and disease. Signal Transduct Target Ther. 2023 Sep 13;8(1):345. doi: 10.1038/s41392-023-01569-3. PMID: 37699892; PMCID: PMC10497558","Nakrani MN, Wineland RH, Anjum F. Physiology, Glucose Metabolism. 2023 Jul 17. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 32809434.","Chandel NS. Carbohydrate Metabolism. Cold Spring Harb Perspect Biol. 2021 Jan 4;13(1):a040568. doi: 10.1101/cshperspect.a040568. PMID: 33397651; PMCID: PMC7778149."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64078"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17883"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64078","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/64078"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-12T15:54:17+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-12T15:55:27+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10597"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78734"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"upd